</td></tr></table><hr class="messageboxline" size="1">
I started gaming with Melee Wizard and Deathtest... well, actualy, I started before that but they were the first non-mainstream games I got that were solidly in fantasy and I was hooked.  I got the original D&D boxed set when it first came out and we tried, oh how we tried, to get that system to work.  We did RP, but, we ended up with the first of the AD&D rules <b></b>(read: the first set of rules that were written in something that was not arcane and was reasonably understandable<b></b>).  Things went downhill from there: STTRPG, C&S, Runequest, Clawlaw <b></b>(or whatever it's called<b></b>), Fantasy Hero, Morrow Project, EarthDawn <b></b>(where Gnarl came from<b></b>), and a host of others whose names escape me <b></b>(and it's driving me nuts that I can't remember some of them<b></b>).<BR>
<BR>
I gamed with Beggly and the crowd in a 2 year game of super hero roleplay <b></b>(Gads, this is frustrating, Hero games published it, what IS the name of it... not like I don't have 4 copies on my shelf<b></b>) GM'd by Beggly, and two other close friends in the Phoenix area.  I also went out of my way to at least understand every game out there well enough to roll a character up in it, so, though I can't say I've campained in every game system, I can say that when I was working for Flying Buffalo Inc, I made it a pint to at least roll up a character in every RPG and understood enough of the mechanics to play.  Quite the undertaking but not nearly as difficult as trying to GM in each of them.<BR>
<BR>
I'm also an avid war gamer <b></b>(or was<b></b>) which is why games like Medal of Honor: Allied Assault and Return to Castle Wolfenstein appeal to me greatly.  Some of the first person shooters, though truly only Hack and Slash games, have very well laid out plot lines and a story that flows well... in fact, the good ones ALL have such a story lines, the bad ones done <b></b>(Quake, though a wonderful engine for FPS, doesn't fit the bill because there was never any rhyme or reason to the characters, just spastic attempts at killing each other... the latest rendition, in fact, was nothing but a constant frag fest, though I could play it and enjoy the competition, it really had nothing to keep ones interest<b></b>).<BR>
<BR>
There you have it... been playing something since the early 70s <b></b>(72 iirc<b></b>), so, call it 30 years... not as long as Beggly can claim but far longer than my father would be pleased to hear about.  <img align="absmiddle" src="HTTP://www.clawpaw.com/eq/sw/forums/images/smile.gif"><BR>
<BR>
Gnarl<br></td></tr></table>
